    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Broadlands, | Sandown, I.W.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Ap 3</date>
                    <salute>My dear Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>It is much easier to ask questions than answer them. “Pulmonaria” does not exactly answer either of your propositions. It does not “look up to the sky nor down to the ground”.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>After looking at it several times I brought M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Fox<ref target="#foot.f3"/> &amp; held a council or Inquest upon the body. It is agreed that P: angustifolia looks up, but not <hi rend="underline">very much up</hi>.<ref target="#foot.f4"/> “P. grandiflora” (as Sir P Egertons Gardener gave it me) but which I never can see any differences between it &amp; the broader leaved varieties (this has a bit of tape tied round it.) does not look quite so much up.<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>But decidedly neither look “down to Earth”.</p> 
<figure type="diagram"> 
<p>[DIAG HERE]</p> </figure> 
<p>These lines are about the angle, upwards decidedly—</p>
<p>In haste yours very truly | W D Fox</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="annotations">
                <note><hi rend="italic">Top of letter</hi>: ‘(<hi rend="italic">Used under Pulmonaria</hi>)’ <hi rend="italic">pencil, square brackets in ms</hi></note>
                <note><hi rend="italic">End of letter</hi>: ‘(say flowers [‘f’ <hi rend="italic">over</hi> ‘F’] projecting obliquely upwards.)’<ref target="#foot.f6"/> <hi rend="italic">ink, square brackets in ms</hi></note>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10923F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from W. E. Darwin, 4 April 1877</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD had evidently written to either Fox or <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1245.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Erasmus Darwin</ref> regarding the placement of flowers of <hi rend="italic">Pulmonaria</hi> (the genus of lungworts) on the stem; however, no letter on the subject has been found. See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10922F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from W. E. Darwin, [25 March? 1877]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1711.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ellen Sophia Fox</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><hi rend="italic">Pulmonaria angustifolia</hi> is narow-leaved lungwort.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><hi rend="italic">Pulmonaria grandiflora</hi> is a synonym of <hi rend="italic">P. saccharata</hi> Bethlehem lungwort. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_7947.xml">William Muir</ref> was head gardener at Oulton Park, the home of Philip de Malpas Grey-Egerton.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2613.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Forms of flowers</hi></ref>, p. 110, CD noted, ‘with <hi rend="italic">Pulmonaria angustifolia</hi>, it is evident, from the corolla projecting obliquely upwards, that pollen is much more likely to fall on, or to be carried by insects down to the stigma of the short-styled than of the long-styled flowers’.</note>
        </div>        
            
